I want to know this and I want to know that.

33:03.250 --> 33:04.570
And are you ever going to talk about this?

33:04.710 --> 33:05.590
And are you ever going to talk about that?

33:06.030 --> 33:09.010
And she said, either write me a long letter back or write another book.

33:10.230 --> 33:14.030
So I laughingly shared that letter with my editor and.

33:15.750 --> 33:18.650
Started thinking about the answers to those questions, but it hadn't gotten

33:18.650 --> 33:21.730
beyond that point until the first book started to sell really well.

33:22.310 --> 33:24.770
And then my editor said, gee, you ought to think about the fourth book.

33:25.190 --> 33:28.530
And I said, well, the only way I'll do a fourth book if it's the final book,

33:28.530 --> 33:30.470
because I don't want an endless series.

33:31.410 --> 33:34.910
If I can make this the final book and under these conditions, then I will,

33:34.990 --> 33:37.070
I will write it and I will answer Annie's question.

33:37.630 --> 33:40.330
So the fourth book is going to be to answer any questions.

33:41.230 --> 33:42.990
I mean, that's what started the whole thing.

33:43.870 --> 33:44.850
Dan McCaffrey's fault.

33:46.090 --> 33:46.690
Buzzer heart.

33:47.570 --> 33:51.850
You have, you apparently have other things going on now.

33:52.350 --> 33:54.650
Science fiction, I assume science fiction works.

33:55.370 --> 33:57.090
Would you want to share any of that with us?

33:57.230 --> 33:58.050
What you're working on?

33:59.690 --> 34:06.350
Yeah, I finished a book in October with a man who's been my best friend

34:06.350 --> 34:10.210
since we were 12 years old, Ralph Mylis, called the Sarencennacles,

34:10.250 --> 34:11.950
which has nothing to do with the series.

34:12.730 --> 34:15.570
It has to do with Ralph spending three years in the desert in Saudi Arabia

34:15.570 --> 34:18.330
and baking his brain and coming back and thinking he wanted to write

34:18.330 --> 34:21.250
science fiction after 20 years as being a successful accountant.

34:22.570 --> 34:26.190
And I'll have better sense in that and understanding the financial side of this world.

34:27.210 --> 34:31.410
We wrote that in, took most of last year to write that.

34:32.490 --> 34:38.870
I just finished the fourth book in the series, finished the next little

34:38.870 --> 34:41.070
last draft right before I came here to AggieCon.

34:41.930 --> 34:46.890
And I have a proposal in front of Bandim now for a new series called

34:46.890 --> 34:52.750
the Double Spiral War, which is going to involve a lot of my experiences

34:52.750 --> 34:55.750
in Vietnam, but also a lot of my reading on wars in general.

34:58.930 --> 35:05.950
It's really a kind of, it's a 485,000 story about a war, but it breaks neatly

35:05.950 --> 35:11.190
into five sections because of the scope of the war.

35:12.870 --> 35:19.310
And it's a viewpoint on war that I wanted to use in telling a story

35:19.310 --> 35:22.950
about a war that I really haven't seen done the way I wanted it to do.

35:23.430 --> 35:24.890
And why, what the way I wanted it done.

35:25.310 --> 35:27.990
So that's probably going to be my next project.

35:28.210 --> 35:34.230
Is it going to be closer to forever war or build with Lactic Hero or Starship Troopers

35:34.790 --> 35:36.850
or it's going to be something different?

35:37.390 --> 35:39.190
Well, I hope it's going to be something different.

35:41.650 --> 35:49.110
Just the first, the first chapter in the first book opens up with the leader

35:49.110 --> 35:55.250
of the opposition, who by the end of that chapter has become a very sympathetic

35:55.250 --> 36:02.210
character. I expect the readers to really like him because he is a very human

36:05.450 --> 36:10.670
compassionate individual, but because of what happens to him and because personally

36:10.670 --> 36:15.110
and politically. I mean, he ends up being the antagonist.

36:15.150 --> 36:16.790
He's on the wrong side of the fence.

36:17.910 --> 36:21.610
But part of what I want to do is to show that you can be on the wrong side of the

36:21.610 --> 36:23.310
fence and be a good guy, quote unquote.

36:24.130 --> 36:30.610
You can be a lovable, likable human being with all those positive traits we think

36:30.610 --> 36:38.410
of in people and be on the wrong side in the wrong place and end up having to pay

36:38.410 --> 36:45.430
for it. And so I'm starting that book from the viewpoint of this very likable

36:45.430 --> 36:46.270
antagonist.

36:50.490 --> 36:52.990
Okay, I'll ask you kind of a general question.

36:52.990 --> 37:03.710
And you distributed books, whatever your job with Ballantyne was, what's the

37:03.710 --> 37:09.070
future going to be like for the genre of science fiction next five or 10 years?

37:09.390 --> 37:11.370
Books are getting pre-dammed expensive.

37:12.630 --> 37:16.510
You don't just go in and save your pocket change, buy them anymore.

37:17.450 --> 37:23.130
Is there going to be more, fewer big companies, but fewer companies controlling

37:23.130 --> 37:25.750
all publishing? What is your outlook on it?

37:26.590 --> 37:28.430
All right, excuse me.

37:28.450 --> 37:28.990
I don't know.

37:29.930 --> 37:35.130
I've been in the book business since 1969 and I've decided that the only constant

37:35.130 --> 37:42.170
is change. And I've decided that if a rumor comes along about some change in the

37:42.170 --> 37:45.570
industry, the more absurd the rumor, the better its chances of coming true.

37:46.990 --> 37:51.470
It's extremely difficult industry to predict on a short term basis.

37:51.650 --> 37:55.470
It looks to me like for a short term, we are going to have fewer companies,

37:55.650 --> 38:06.330
fewer markets, more formula type science fiction, less science fiction that

38:06.330 --> 38:08.910
stretches, that reaches out.

38:08.970 --> 38:10.290
But I think that will change.

38:10.450 --> 38:11.910
I don't think that's a permanent condition.

38:12.030 --> 38:14.550
I think that's part of the temporary flux that the market is in.

38:15.250 --> 38:18.230
I think we will see houses like Tor get stronger.

38:18.950 --> 38:20.830
They are very financially stable.

38:21.030 --> 38:22.970
They have done well with the books that they've done.

38:23.070 --> 38:23.870
They will get stronger.

38:24.330 --> 38:29.050
I think other smaller companies will in one way or another begin to fill the

38:29.050 --> 38:32.110
vacuum that's been left by all this conglomeratization.

38:33.330 --> 38:38.150
And that we will see again another expansion, whether it takes three years or

38:38.150 --> 38:39.490
five years, I have no way of knowing.

38:39.770 --> 38:41.330
But I think we'll see another expansion.

38:41.970 --> 38:45.030
The thing that scares me is what you mentioned first, and that is the price of

38:45.030 --> 38:45.310
the books.

38:45.790 --> 38:49.190
I figured out when I was running a retail store about seven, eight years ago that

38:50.490 --> 38:53.990
somewhere in the like 1990 that the average paperback book was going to cost

38:53.990 --> 38:54.850
$10.97.

38:55.430 --> 38:59.410
But then the average retail clerk at the same time was going to be make like

38:59.410 --> 39:00.690
2250 an hour.

39:00.690 --> 39:01.730
All right.

39:01.970 --> 39:05.030
If assuming it's a certain level of inflation.

39:07.210 --> 39:11.770
The question is, will we be able to overcome those same psychological barriers

39:11.770 --> 39:14.830
that we overcame with gasoline and the rising price of bread?

39:15.690 --> 39:18.970
I mean, I can remember buying bread for 10 cents a loaf and I can remember buying

39:18.970 --> 39:20.370
gas for 17 cents a gallon.

39:21.130 --> 39:21.150
Right.

39:22.070 --> 39:26.930
Now, you know, we rejoice if we can get gas and then 91 cents, 89 cents and

39:26.930 --> 39:29.790
everybody rushes to the corner for 89 cents a gallon gasoline and it'll go back

39:29.790 --> 39:30.990
up to a dollar or something again.

39:31.470 --> 39:35.330
And if we can overcome that psychological barrier of 10.97 for a paperback,

39:36.530 --> 39:38.790
maybe, maybe we'll survive, but I don't know.

39:39.050 --> 39:42.590
That's the part that scares me is the inflation prices as much as anything

39:42.590 --> 39:42.870
else.

39:42.930 --> 39:46.390
But I think what part of what we'll see is more and more of a shift over to the

39:46.390 --> 39:50.690
trade paperbacks that they will take the place of most of the hard covers

39:51.250 --> 39:55.990
because the hard covers will just get too expensive and people regardless of the

39:55.990 --> 40:00.370
ratio, people will just be unwilling to pay hard cover prices.

40:00.370 --> 40:02.930
So we'll see more trade paper.

40:03.250 --> 40:09.010
We'll see more new books done in trade paper by lesser known authors that

40:09.010 --> 40:12.250
might have been done in hard cover at one time by double day or Berkeley or

40:12.250 --> 40:13.010
someone else.

40:13.930 --> 40:16.450
And that may take some of the pressure off the market.

40:17.250 --> 40:19.250
So trade paperbacks are here to stay?

40:19.610 --> 40:20.910
I think so, yes.

40:21.330 --> 40:25.410
I think I think the thing that will cinch it and I keep waiting for

40:26.030 --> 40:29.430
publishers are not very progressive people, but I keep waiting for the

40:29.430 --> 40:34.250
publishers to do and trade back, trade paper publishing what they did years and

40:34.250 --> 40:36.070
years ago in mass market publishing.

40:36.190 --> 40:40.290
And that is go to a standard size because what will cinch the market is when

40:40.290 --> 40:43.790
they go to a standard trade size, the same way they did with a mass market size,

40:43.890 --> 40:47.310
that means that all those places out there that you can put those books will

40:47.310 --> 40:51.670
go to a standard size rack, which means they can be handled in the same way,

40:51.690 --> 40:55.610
which means they can get much deeper into the distribution channels, which

40:55.610 --> 40:58.590
means they'll get much wider distribution and better sales.

40:58.590 --> 40:59.190
Right.

40:59.650 --> 41:04.350
And until they do that, until the publishers finally beat their heads

41:04.350 --> 41:07.970
against each other and are willing to settle on a size, they're going to limit

41:07.970 --> 41:09.530
the saleability of those things.

41:09.530 --> 41:10.310
But I think they will.

41:10.450 --> 41:12.390
I think the market will demand that they do that.

41:12.750 --> 41:15.190
And when they do, then we will see a new class.

41:15.570 --> 41:17.750
We will have an a sense mass market trade books.

41:18.690 --> 41:19.710
They will be bigger.

41:19.890 --> 41:25.030
They'll be slightly better bound, maybe slightly better paper, bigger type

41:25.030 --> 41:29.350
faces anyway, easier to read and they'll come in standard sizes and they'll show

41:29.350 --> 41:33.170
up in racks to be a rack of mass market books and a rack of trade books.

41:34.210 --> 41:36.210
And that's the direction I think they have to go.

41:36.450 --> 41:38.190
You remember all the different sizes mass market books.

41:38.350 --> 41:38.470
Yeah.

41:38.610 --> 41:43.970
You know, if you're any collector knows, right, they, as a collector, I know you

41:43.970 --> 41:48.790
said in one book that it looks like that's that may trade paperbacks may save

41:48.790 --> 41:50.890
the industry, but as a collector, I hate you.

41:51.510 --> 41:52.970
But if they're here, they're here.

41:52.970 --> 41:53.690
I like it.

41:53.730 --> 41:59.290
But yeah, I have, I have Larry Newman's, the magic goes away.

41:59.510 --> 42:03.150
And it's, damn it's, I could barely get it on my shelf and then I've got some

42:03.150 --> 42:05.550
little ones and there's all different sizes.

42:06.370 --> 42:10.630
Well, if you look, even, even with the standardization of size on mass market

42:10.630 --> 42:13.690
books, if you look at mass market books, they are different sizes, right?

42:13.910 --> 42:16.450
Not widths, but heights, right?

42:17.110 --> 42:19.650
Ban, even in the Bantam line, there are different heights.

42:19.650 --> 42:24.570
And what they have started to do is they've knocked off like an eight or three

42:24.570 --> 42:29.630
sixteenths of an inch from what was their standard height because they figured

42:29.630 --> 42:34.490
if they, if they knocked off three sixteenths of an inch on each book and

42:34.490 --> 42:39.630
they were doing a printing of 250,000 books that for the same amount of money,

42:39.630 --> 42:43.150
they were getting like an extra 5,000 books out of the same roll of paper.

42:43.830 --> 42:45.830
Now, paper's gotten extremely expensive, right?

42:46.530 --> 42:50.870
So if you can get an extra 5,000 books out of that same roll of paper, right?

42:51.130 --> 42:55.030
You've saved some money and it's, but it really messes up your shelf when you

42:55.030 --> 42:57.790
have a series and they stair step along the shelf.

42:58.910 --> 43:03.330
I have two copies of Bill DeGalactico, the first edition that Harry signed

43:03.330 --> 43:07.490
yesterday and one of them is at least a quarter of an inch is not more higher.

43:07.690 --> 43:11.530
I mean, they, it's the same edition of the same book, same printing.

43:11.530 --> 43:12.030
Yeah.

43:12.050 --> 43:14.690
And Ace Doubles, my Ace Doubles.

43:14.870 --> 43:15.070
Yeah.

43:15.150 --> 43:16.870
Kind of stair step like that too.

43:17.150 --> 43:17.590
It's interesting.

43:17.890 --> 43:18.650
Jagged Peaks.

43:19.050 --> 43:20.610
Any questions, Mr. Carson?

43:21.790 --> 43:22.390
Hmm.

43:23.250 --> 43:24.330
No, no.

43:24.670 --> 43:26.390
Well, maybe one.

43:29.210 --> 43:31.110
You didn't ask me writing questions.

43:32.570 --> 43:34.890
No, no mechanics thereof.

43:35.330 --> 43:37.370
Just a few mechanics type questions.

43:37.370 --> 43:42.910
Whenever you start to write something like the windhover, what came first?

43:43.350 --> 43:48.470
Characters, plot, character with a problem.

43:50.190 --> 43:54.410
That's, that's how most of my stories begin as character with a problem.

43:55.330 --> 43:59.250
I write short stories that are unsayable because the characters have

43:59.250 --> 44:04.230
problems that are either so bizarre or so obscene.

44:06.250 --> 44:10.610
Or something else that even though the problem gets resolved by the end of the

44:10.610 --> 44:13.450
story that no one's really interested, that's fine because I just write them for

44:13.450 --> 44:13.730
fun.

44:13.830 --> 44:17.710
They're characters who pop into my head with this particular problem and I let

44:17.710 --> 44:21.250
them run through that section of their lives until they solve the problem and

44:21.250 --> 44:24.430
then they go back in the drawer and I've gotten them out of my head, which is the

44:24.430 --> 44:25.170
most important thing.

44:25.650 --> 44:33.890
But I start with a character with a problem and very shortly thereafter, I

44:33.890 --> 44:37.030
have two to three weeks for a novel length work.

44:37.430 --> 44:40.710
I have a very good idea of how the story ends.

44:41.830 --> 44:45.530
All right, so I have a beginning and an ending and the middle is just, it's like

44:45.530 --> 44:45.990
standing.

44:46.410 --> 44:49.130
I remember as a kid standing and the first time I went through Tennessee and

44:49.130 --> 44:53.230
standing on one of those overlooks and looking out across to the mountains on

44:53.230 --> 44:55.850
the other side and it was nothing but fog and mist in the bottom.

44:56.010 --> 44:58.450
Well, that's kind of how I feel when I get ready to start a novel.

44:58.870 --> 45:01.990
I know where I am and I know the mountain is on the other side, but what's in

45:01.990 --> 45:02.430
the middle there?

45:02.790 --> 45:05.190
I don't know, except you have to go down and you have to come back up in order

45:05.190 --> 45:05.630
to get there.

45:06.390 --> 45:11.510
And then that middle resolves itself in a very vague way as I begin the story.

45:12.650 --> 45:17.750
And I found the more that I try to put my characters through paces in the

45:17.750 --> 45:20.930
middle to do certain things, the less cooperative they become.

45:21.350 --> 45:24.930
So what I try to do then is tap them back in the line when they start pushing

45:24.930 --> 45:26.530
the plot too far away.

45:26.830 --> 45:28.430
I think I'll never get to the end this way.

45:28.490 --> 45:31.510
If you guys keep going left edge, little right, make me happy.

45:32.130 --> 45:34.850
So I'd nudge them back to the right a little bit and then they head back

45:34.850 --> 45:37.550
and then they go way off too far to the right and you have to nudge them back

45:37.550 --> 45:38.030
to the left.

45:38.750 --> 45:42.810
It's a strange process, especially when they come alive in the back of your

45:42.810 --> 45:45.730
head and they start saying things and doing things that you didn't expect them

45:45.730 --> 45:46.070
to do.

45:46.590 --> 45:48.630
Sheryl's pregnancy is a perfect example of that.

45:49.270 --> 45:52.210
I mean, she wasn't supposed to get pregnant for another six months in this

45:52.210 --> 45:54.670
story because I had to get them where they were going first, right?

45:55.050 --> 45:57.310
I was going to have her get pregnant someplace safe.

45:57.950 --> 46:01.110
Oh, no, she had to get pregnant and she and Gerard had to argue about it.

46:01.110 --> 46:02.770
And then I was angry at both of them.

46:02.830 --> 46:05.550
And then I had to back off and take five pages out of the manuscript, say,

46:05.570 --> 46:08.370
wait a minute, take them back to the beginning of that scene, say, it's your

46:08.370 --> 46:10.970
problem, you work it out, I'll write it down.

46:11.090 --> 46:12.230
You just tell me what's right now.

46:12.450 --> 46:15.550
And so I let them argue at the problem and solve their difficulties and it was

46:15.550 --> 46:15.990
all fine.

46:16.530 --> 46:18.690
And I learned a valuable lesson.

46:18.810 --> 46:22.330
Keep your cotton picking hands off their lives when they're doing it themselves.

46:23.350 --> 46:25.070
When they're struggling with it themselves.

46:26.230 --> 46:29.250
When you get your characters going, they become their own little entities.

46:29.850 --> 46:30.430
Oh, yes.

46:30.430 --> 46:31.190
Oh, yes.

46:31.410 --> 46:36.750
They, when Ralph and I did our book, one of the things that happened was we had,

46:36.850 --> 46:43.490
we started with a male protagonist and then a minor protagonist who was female.

46:44.670 --> 46:49.750
And she came alive for me about the same time that he came alive for Ralph.

46:50.610 --> 46:51.630
And so he was right.

46:51.750 --> 46:54.730
Ralph was writing the first draft and he was putting words in her mouth.

46:54.910 --> 46:57.370
And then when I was reading it and getting ready to write the second draft,

46:57.430 --> 46:58.870
she was in the back of my head screaming.

46:58.870 --> 47:00.270
No, no, no, I wouldn't say that.

47:00.270 --> 47:01.630
I wouldn't, I wouldn't react like that.

47:01.950 --> 47:05.350
So I'd get on the phone to Ralph and I'd say, Calissa says that she wouldn't

47:05.350 --> 47:06.230
react like this.

47:06.750 --> 47:09.330
And he said, well, we'll work it out tomorrow at our story conference.

47:09.410 --> 47:12.470
And we'd sit there for eight hours trying to hash out dialogue between a

47:12.470 --> 47:15.850
character who was alive in his head and a character who was alive in my head.

47:16.010 --> 47:21.030
And he had to have enough sense of that to go back then and write first draft

47:21.030 --> 47:24.830
material based on what I had told him about a character who was living in my

47:24.830 --> 47:25.070
head.

47:25.590 --> 47:28.670
The only thing that saved us was that some character didn't come alive that

47:28.670 --> 47:30.410
way for both of us, right?

47:30.570 --> 47:32.050
Who then would have been schizophrenic.

47:32.670 --> 47:35.350
He'd have been alive one way and Ralph said it another way in my head.

47:35.470 --> 47:37.050
We'd probably had to do something.

47:37.250 --> 47:38.650
We'd have to divide him into two characters.

47:40.710 --> 47:41.550
Bizarre, bizarre.

47:42.370 --> 47:42.750
Interesting.

47:43.070 --> 47:43.270
Yeah.

47:44.090 --> 47:44.410
Yeah.

47:44.610 --> 47:46.790
That's something that always ceases to amaze us.

47:47.230 --> 47:49.950
We never ceases to always ceases.

47:52.590 --> 47:57.510
Just the writing process and not being writers, but being extremely interested

47:57.510 --> 47:58.190
in the process.

47:58.550 --> 48:01.530
And we've heard time and time again how the characters just take over and

48:01.530 --> 48:03.070
that's just that blows us away.

48:03.390 --> 48:07.230
I can think of characters and I can think of stories and that's where it stops.

